column5: This course will allow students to gain real-world experiencesýand prepare themselves to work as professional dog trainersýpost-graduation. The course will cover contract development,ýgroup class content, developing materials for clients, andýlearning how to implement these items in a real group course.ýCommunity members will be invited to complete the group classesýstudents design (aggression and reactivity cases will not beýaccepted due to liability purposes). Students must haveýpreviously completed ANZ 321 and ANZ 321L or receive instructorýpermission.

column5: This course, part of the proposed Anthrozoology EntrepreneurshipýCertificate program offered in conjunction with the BusinessýDepartment at Carroll, offers students an opportunity to create aýbusiness plan for either a for-profit animal-related business, orýfor running an animal-related non-profit organization. The courseýfocuses on the sequence of events that take place starting withýthe original idea for a new animal-related product or service toýactual beginning a new business. It emphasizes the understandingýof the various "stages" of development that any new product orýservice must pass, and the various activities each functionalýarea of the organization must contribute, in order to have aýsuccessful business launch.
column93: 01/17/2024-05/08/2024 Lecture Monday, Wednesday, Friday 11:00AM - 11:50AM, Perkins Call Canine Center, Room 101

column5: Canine Olfaction Science, Forensics, and Law.ýThis is an advanced course for those interested in a career withýworking dogs, primarily concerning allýforms of Scent Work. The anatomy and neurobiology of canineýolfaction will be discussed in depth,ýalong with the external aerodynamics and internal fluid dynamicsýof olfaction. Training and selectionýof working dogs versus non-working dogs will be discussed. Weýwill delve into the various scent workýdisciplines available to working dog handlers, Narcoticsýdetection, explosives detection, humanýremains detection, search and rescue,conservation work andýmedical detection applications for dogs.ýRecord keeping, certification,and deployment protocol for all ofýthe aforementioned.Molecularýmovement, and how scent flows in various environments and underývarious conditions will beýcovered.We will be covering how dogs can be utilized to obtainýforensic evidence in crime scenes, andýhow to best be prepared for court testimony in those instances.ýLegal implications and parameters ofýutilizing K9 in both the public and private sectors will beýcovered as well.The information in thisýcourse will be distilled and presented in such a way as to giveýthe student the best advantage whenýapplying for a position in the rapidly growing scent workýindustry.

column5: This course will provide an introduction to Catholicýanthropology: understandings of the origin, journey, and end ofýthe human person. We will read a selection of ancient throughýcontemporary thinkers in order to investigate three central areasýof inquiry about the human. Creation: What does it mean to beýcreated? To be made in God's image? Sin and Redemption: What doesýit mean to be creatures marred by sin and redeemed by Christ?ýWhat is the role of grace? Sanctification and Salvation: What isýthe end for which we hope, and what does the full flourishing ofýthe human entail? We will use our investigations to considerýchallenging issues which, although perennial, involve discerniblyýpressing questions as, in the phrase of Gaudium et Spes, "signsýof the times" (#22). We will look at sex and gender, race,ýdisability, suffering, and the social dimension per se of beingýhuman, and ask how the Catholic Tradition thinks about theseýdifferent aspects of being human, as well as how these issues mayýchallenge us to clarify and enrich our grasp of what it means toýbe human.

column5: This course will study visual art in the Catholic Tradition,ýexamining the thought and art of two periods in which controversyýabout the fittingness of images in the life and worship of theýChurch led to moments of artistic flourishing. In the East theýIconoclast Controversy of the 8th-9th centuries catalyzed aýrenewal of Byzantine iconography and the veneration of images ofýChrist. In the West a new era of iconoclasm arose during theýReformation. Counter-Reformation artistic representations ofýChrist again emerged as part of a renewal of worship andýcatechesis. The course will study closely several icons andýpaintings from these periods, as well as the biblical andýconciliar texts at play in the controversies, all within theirýhistorical contexts.

column4: William Shakespeare (in As You Like It) is credited to haveýwritten, "all the world's a stage." More recently, sociologistýErving Goffman (in The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life)ýoffered a sort of disagreement (you know, the sort that's not) inýsaying, "All the world is not, of course, a stage, but theýcrucial ways in which it isn't are not easy to specify." In thisýcourse we will take up the perspective coined by Shakespeare andýimplicated by Goffman -- that the world is a stage and we are itsýplayers -- by examining communication as it occurs on the "stage"ýof everyday life. We will observe and write about communicationýin situ (which means in the context of its production) and lookýinto the impact of communication action (e.g. teasing, givingýcompliments, doing 'small talk') on human activities such asýcommunication ritual and identities. This course is designed toýhelp you become a more effective writer, but it also promises toýmake you a more astute observer of human action.

column4: This course explores the intersection between a sustainable worldýand creation of enterprise value. Benjamin Franklin suggestedýthat it was possible for individuals and companies to do welýlwhile also doing good. The current view of this concept goesýwell beyond philanthropy. Our class will begin with theýcautionary tale presented in Dr. Seuss' book, The Lorax. As ourýclass reflects on the possibility of doing well while doing good,ýwe will critically evaluate a series of readings, includingýwritings of Pope Francis. The course takes a multidisciplinaryýapproach to examine the evolution of the language of business,ýthe ethical implications of sustainability reporting, and theýcurrent response to increased financial market emphasis on socialýand environmental justice in the pursuit of economic growth.ý"Pretty much all the stuff you need to know is in Dr. Seuss."ýPresident Barack Obama.

column4: Fly Fishing: Meditation and Practice.ýFly-fishing is a unique combination of art, science, andýmindfulness. It is the pinnacle of fishingýmethods and practice and, as such, it's history and its eleganceýhas inspired poems and prose. To those outside of the fly-fishingýworld, it may seem difficult, obsessive and unnecessary. In thisýcourse we explore the technical and spiritual aspects of thisýelegant activity with the goal to bring individuals to understandýthe field. Entomology, ichthyology, fly-tying and casting are theýtechnical aspect. We explore too the spiritual aspects of thoughtýand meditation as it applies to any practice. This is anýintroductory course to liberal arts education. Students willýlearn how to read, write, think, and converse in a collegiateýacademic community while they practice the art and science ofýfishing with the fly.

column4: We live in a media environment unlike anything that has comeýbefore in American history.  The 24-hour news cycle and constantýbarrage of information can leave us bewildered, wondering whatýsources to trust and what facts to believe.  With cable newsýchannels, online newspapers, partisan blogs, twitter andýfacebook, is there actually a way to make sense of what'sýhappening out there-to arrive at a well-reasoned and informedýunderstanding of the important issues that face us?  This courseýwill illuminate current social, political, and economic issues byýplacing them in their historical context, and will provideýstudents with the investigative and analytical tools necessary toýdistinguish fact from mere assertion, evidence from opinion. ýIssues will include health care, immigration, climate change,ýracial and economic inequality, and others that will no doubtýarise over the course of the semester.  Through investigating andýdiscussing all of these topics, we will come to see that the bestýway to understand our present is first to understand our past.

column5: The title of this course might sound cheaply provocative andýnaughty, but it deals with important features of how we talk andýhow we write.  In this course we examine the motivations and theýforms of our truth-telling, our lies, and our-well-you know. ýSince Core 110 is writing-intensive, we will pay particularýattention to how college-level writers argue and how we canýbecome better at it.  We will do so by studying the writings ofýHarry Frankfurt, George Orwell, Plato, and William Shakespeare. ýWe will also examine the emerging role of artificial intelligenceýin communication and how it complicates our central inquiry. Inýall our investigations, we aim to become more critical readersýand more precise in our thinking and writing.

column5: With increasing concerns about pandemics and emerging zoonoticýdisease, One Health is a multidisciplinary approach focused onýthe intersection of human, animal and environmental health. Thisýcutting edge discipline combines our current understanding of theýscience of medicine, veterinary care, and the biology ofýinfectious disease to better predict when and where outbreaks areýmost likely to occur and to derive solutions to mitigate theirýeffects. We will explore the literature in this crossoverýdiscipline and lessons learned from past and recent epidemics andýpandemics. Students will learn how to read, write and converse inýan academic manner that best exemplifies a liberal artsýeducation.

column5: This elective class is intended to give the student anýintroduction to real-world developmentýusing a modern web-application framework as used by commercialýdevelopment staff. Theýstudent will use Java (or, optionally Kotlin) to create anýapplication to perform a task of theirýchoice, all the while learning about web frameworks, HTML,ýdependency-injection, and unitýtesting. The course will cover a wide variety of topics includingýsoftware development,ýconfiguration, deployment, and monitoring. Specific technologiesýand frameworks to be coveredýinclude, Java 8, HTML5, Spring/Spring Boot, Docker, Hibernate,ýSLF4J, JUnit, MySQL(SQL),ýRedis (NoSQL), and web-services (RestFUL). Time permitting, theýstudents will upload theirýcompleted projects to an AWS instance in the Amazon cloud andýverify that it can be accessedýfrom anywhere in the world.

column5: This course provides hands-on experience in integrating existingýhydrologic and topographic data, calibrating hydrologic andýhydraulic models, and generating analyses for engineering designýand land planning. This course presents background theory andýallows practical application in the lab to correctlyýconceptualize, construct, and calibrate hydrologic and hydraulicýmodels using industry standard software applications. Thisýstart-to-finish experience will allow the participant to performýapplied engineering modeling in government, industry, andýacademic settings.ýýTheoretical groundings, software limitations, applicability, andýcurrent topics within the field will be discussed during lectureýmeetings. Practical lab work will be subdivided into two parts:ý(1) quantification of flow and (2) characterization of flow. Theýfirst half of the course will focus on hydrologic modeling, withýapplied lab work using a U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE)ýHydrologic Engineering Center rainfall-runoff software, HEC-HMSý(Hydrologic Modeling Software). HEC-HMS estimates surface waterýdischarge in a basin catchment area given localized input data,ýincluding rainfall and land use. ýýThe second half of the course will shift to hydraulic modeling ofýsurface flow, and will include a software shift to another USACEýprogram, HEC-RAS (River Analysis System). HEC-RAS enables waterýsurface profile computations, flooding analysis, andýbridge/culvert hydraulic design given runoff quantity, channelýgeometry, and manning value. A third software, HEC-GeoRAS, willýbe introduced to obtain results that can be readily used in anyýGIS software, especially useful for mapping inundation, includingýregulatory floodplains, channel migration zones, dam breaches,ýand more.

column5: French Cooking & GastronomyýThis elective course is designed to provide an overview of Frenchýcooking andýgastronomy, through theory and hands-on practice. As we willýtechniques, traditions, chefs, and specialties of French cuisine,ýstudents willýunderstand its diversity, influences, and history, as well as itsýimportance in theýFrench and francophone culture and society and experiment itýthrough cookingýand tasting during the class period. Students will also beýintroduced to someýtraditional dishes from the Francophone world. Bon appétit!ýThis course is a dual-level course designed for both studentsýwith backgroundýin French and students with no previous knowledge of French.ýThough Englishýwill be the main language in class, French will be used as oftenýas possibleýduring the class period.

column5: Violent plunderers? Swashbuckling heroes? Lawless murderers?ýPirates, it might be argued, defy a neat two-word definition.ýInstead, they challenged and served political power structuresýalthough here the proper terms is corsairs, lived, and often diedýfollowing a code of morals, and are an indelible part of manyýparts of history. This class traces piracy from antiquity to theýpresent, revealing these men and women as the nuanced historicýactors they were.

column4: This course provides a guide for students to assess their ownýlearning styles and create a plan to bestýsupport their academic needs. Students will be introduced toýorganizational strategies, theories ofýlearning, and types of memory. Through a series of multimodalýactivities, they will explore their ownýcognitive strengths, examine executive functions, and reviewýcommon barriers to learning. The class willýlearn how to collect data, assess their own progress, and adjustýlearning strategies as needed. Studentsýwill leave the course with a detailed plan on how to best supportýtheir learning at Carroll and fosterýhabits for future careers.

column5: This course investigates research and theory concerning theýbiological, cognitive, and psychosocial development of a personýfrom conception to death. The course covers lifespan developmentýtopics, investigating biopsychosocial influences during prenatalýdevelopment, infancy, early and middle childhood, adolescence,ýemerging adulthood, middle, and late adulthood, as well as issuesýsurrounding death, dying, and bereavement.

column5: Pathway to Private Practice supports the development ofýspecialized knowledge, skills, values and cognitive and affectiveýprocesses to function effectively as a private practiceýclinician. This course explores federal and state statutes andýregulations which govern clinical social work psychotherapyýpractice. Consistent with the program's focus on culturallyýcompetent and ethical practice, students will learn how to designýan effective framework for a trauma informed business including:ýNASW guidance, qualifications; setting up the practice; models ofýprivate practice; NPI; tax ID; professional liability; forms;ýsupervision; provider panels; marketing; and fees.

column5: Working with children and youth is exciting and rewarding, andýcomes with challenges. Direct Practice with Children and Youthýwill explore several evidence-based practices, including TraumaýFocused CBT, Parent Child Interaction Therapy (PCIT), PlayýTherapy and working with grief in childhood/adolescence. Theýcourse will be focused on practical skills that will enhanceýpractice with this population as well as consider theýdevelopmental phases and neurobiology of childhood andýadolescents.  This class is intended to support the developmentýof research-based skills tools for professional social workýpractice.
column93: 03/18/2024-05/06/2024 Remote (Synchronous) Monday 03:00PM - 04:40PM, Room to be Announced

column5: Experiential Therapy Methods introduces students to experiential,ýwilderness, and adventure therapy approaches, which incorporateýfun and engaging activities (e.g., mountain sports, challengeýcourse activities, problem solving games, icebreaker activities)ýto facilitate experiences of mental health and substance useýdisorder recovery, personal growth, relationship-building, andýimproved resilience. In this course, students will not only learnýabout relevant theory and research, but they will also directlyýparticipate in and facilitate a variety of experientialýactivities. A portion of class will be spent directly engaged inýphysically-active and socially-demanding tasks, though studentsýof all physical ability levels are welcome and encouraged.

column4: American Indian Inquiry and Community Immersion explores socialýwork practice withýIndigenous people, with a special focus on Tribal nations locatedýin Montana. The courseýexplores cultural considerations when serving Indigenous clients,ýtraditional and modernýhealing practices, and the impacts of colonization related toýsocial determinants of health forýAmerican Indians /Native Americans (AI/NA). This course includesýan immersion experienceýfacilitated at Crow and Northern Cheyenne Reservations in easternýMontana. The immersion isýa required component of this course.

column5: This is a hands-on course in Theatrical Theatre ProductionýDesign. Students will learn about a variety of skills related toýbringing a script to stage; including lighting, sound, scenery,ýproperties, and projection design for theatrical productions.ýSkills that will be learned over the course of this semesterýinclude designing, building, and implementing - and a lot ofýout-of-the-box thinking and trouble-shooting to make for aýsuccessful production. A portion of this class will encompassýtaking part in or observing stage productions in the FlexýTheatre. ýýStudents will have research opportunities and prepare projects inýthe following areas of theatrical production: ýo	Light, Sound, Properties, and projection Design andýimplementation, including programming and use of ETC Lighting andýQ-Lab.ýýStudents will also learn and develop the following skills andýabilities: ýo	Technical Production safety and regulationsýo	Interpreting Scripts, creating designs, and reading designýplotsýo	Methods of designing, implementing, programmingýýThe goal for this course is to provide students with a beginningýunderstanding of Technical Theatre Design and implementation.

column4: This course is designed to exploreýcostume design and implementationýfor historical and fantasy shows. Itýexamines the difference betweenýhistorical reconstruction andýcostuming approximations. Throughýreading, discussion, experimentation,ýresearch, and production work,ýstudents will gain knowledge andýpractical skills in costume design,ýorganization and building. Over theýcourse of the semester, students willýshow mastery of the coursework byýsuccessfully building at least two fullýcostumes, designing two shows, andýpresenting their designs in class.
